    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-03-05T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-03-05T17:00:00-05:00" n="673"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d673">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.1731/176: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-03-05T16:00:00-06:00"
                            >March 5, 1936—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>51. My 50, March 4, 7 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>A.</label>
                    <item>At this morning’s conference Minister of Hacienda confirmed yesterday’s
                        decision regarding wheat flour and industrial machinery and definitely
                        agreed to bind upper leather (less 25 per cent as at present) and to reduce
                        duty on lard from 12 to 8 centavos. He, likewise, would be willing to bind
                        all other articles on Schedule 1 but did <pb facs="0908" n="809"
                            xml:id="pg_809"/> not agree to deduct 25 per cent from duty on canned
                        vegetables, canned fruits, and dried fruits.</item>
                    <label>B.</label>
                    <item>Nicaraguan negotiators inquired why pineapples and rum cannot be included
                        in Schedule 2 in accordance with Honduran and Haitian agreements,
                        respectively, in view of coffee (which they state Honduras does not export)
                        being included in Honduran Schedule 2. In this connection and in response to
                        Department’s instruction No. 407 of February 27, it would, in my opinion, be
                        most helpful to Nicaraguan Government to include in an exchange of notes
                        those concessions of interest to Nicaragua selected from other trade
                        agreements but which cannot be written into Schedule 2. Such a procedure
                        would seem to dispose of Nicaraguan inquiry regarding pineapple and rum.
                        Telegraphic instructions would be appreciated on this point.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
